46|12.18| &minus;6.00|$18,677}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Giorgio Cattabeni|1,111|2.03| &minus;0.60|$490}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|James Stephen Kohut|931|1.70|&ndash;| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes|54,533|100.00| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|116|0.21| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|54,649|63.89| }}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Canadian Alliance|&minus;5.52}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|1997|Calgary Southeast|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Reform|Jason Kenney|24,602|55.02| &minus;4.83|$54,180}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PC|Carol Kraychy|10,567|23.63|+3.51 |$60,861}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Patti-Anne Kay|8,131|18.18| +4.55|$43,986}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Jason Ness|1,176|2.63| &minus;0.74|$524}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Natural Law|Neeraj Varma|235|0.52| &minus;0.27| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes|44,711|100.00| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|79|0.18| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|44,790|63.69| }}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Reform|&minus;4.17}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070905194120/http://www.jasonkenney.com/ Official website]\n*{{Canadian Parliament links| parliament = 170319 | parlinfo = 16405 | openparl = jason-kenney}}\n\n{{First Ministers of Canada}}\n{{Alberta MLAs}}\n{{Kenney Ministry}}\n{{PC Alberta}}\n{{Harper Ministry}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Defence}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Labour}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Citizenship and Immigration}}\n{{ABPremiers}}\n{{Alberta politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenney, Jason}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Athol Murray College of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian Alliance MPs]]\n[[Category:Canadian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Canadian Zionists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of Canada]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the 28th Canadian Ministry]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:People from Oakville, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Reform Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the United Conservative Party]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]]\n[[Category:United Conservative Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Merit (Ukraine), 3rd class]]\n[[Category:Premiers of Alberta]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{for|the English cyclist|Jason Kenny}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|size=100%|Hon}}\n| name = Jason Kenney\n| honorific-suffix = [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|PC]] [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|MLA]]\n| image = Jason Kenney in 2019.jpg\n| caption = Jason Kenney in April 2019\n| office = 18th [[Premier of Alberta]]\n| monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| lieutenant_governor = [[Lois Mitchell]]\n| deputy = \n| term_start = April 30, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Rachel Notley]] \n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Additional offices held|titlestyle = border:1px dashed lightgrey}}\n| office1 = [[Leader of the Opposition (Alberta)|Leader of the Opposition in Alberta]]\n| term_start1 = January 4, 2018\n| term_end1 = April 30, 2019\n| premier1 = Rachel Notley\n| predecessor1 = [[Jason Nixon]]\n| successor1 = Rachel Notley \n| office2 = Leader of the [[United Conservative Party]]\n| deputy2 = [[Leela Aheer]]\n| term_start2 = October 28, 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Nathan Cooper (Canadian politician)|Nathan Cooper]] {{small|(interim)}}\n| office3 = Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] for [[Calgary-Lougheed]]\n| term_start3 = December 14, 2017\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[Dave Rodney]]\n| successor3 = \n| office4 = Leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]]\n| term_start4 = March 18, 2017\n| term_end4 = July 24, 2017\n| predecessor4 = [[Ric McIver]] {{small|(interim)}}\n| successor4 = ''Position abolished''\n| office5 = 41st [[Minister of National Defence (Canada)|Minister of National Defence]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Stephen Harper]]\n| term_start5 = February 9, 2015\n| term_end5 = November 4, 2015\n| predecessor5 = [[Rob Nicholson]]\n| successor5 = [[Harjit Sajjan]]\n| office6 = 7th [[Minister of Families, Children and Social Development|Minister of Employment and Social Development]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Stephen Harper]]\n| term_start6 = July 15, 2013\n| term_end6 = February 9, 2015\n| predecessor6 = [[Diane Finley]]\n| successor6 = [[Pierre Poilievre]]\n| office7 = 4th [[Minister of Multiculturalism and Citizenship (Canada)|Minister for Multiculturalism]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Stephen Harper]]\n| term_start7 = August 16, 2013\n| term_end7 = November 4, 2015\n| predecessor7 = Himself <small>(as [[Minister of Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship|Minister of Citizenship, Immigration and Multiculturalism]])</small>\n| successor7 = ''Position abolished''\n| office8 = 17th [[Minister of Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship|Minister of Citizenship, Immigration and Multiculturalism]]\n| primeminister8 = [[Stephen Harper]]\n| term_start8 = October 30, 2008\n| term_end8 = July 15, 2013\n| predecessor8 = [[Diane Finley]]\n| successor8 = [[Chris Alexander (politician)|Chris Alexander]]\n| office9 = Member of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]]<br />for [[Calgary Midnapore]]\n| term_start9 = October 19, 2015\n| term_end9 = September 23, 2016\n| predecessor9 = ''Riding established''\n| successor9 = [[Stephanie Kusie]]\n| office10 = Member of the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]]<br />for [[Calgary Southeast]]\n| term_start10 = June 2, 1997\n| term_end10 = October 19, 2015\n| predecessor10 = [[Jan Brown]]\n| successor10 = ''Riding abolished''\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n| birth_name = Jason Thomas Kenney\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|5|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Oakville, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[United Conservative Party|United Conservative]]\n| otherparty = Federal:<br />[[Reform Party of Canada|Reform]] (1997\u20132000)<br />[[Canadian Alliance|Alliance]] (2000\u20132003)<br />[[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] (2003\u2013present) <br />Provincial:<br />[[Saskatchewan Liberal Party|Liberal]] (Saskatchewan, before 1997)<br />[[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta|Progressive Conservative]] (2016\u20132017)\n| residence = Calgary, Alberta, Canada\n| alma_mater = [[University of San Francisco]] (Did not graduate)\n| relationships = \n}}\n\n'''Jason Thomas Kenney''' [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|PC]] [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|MLA]] (born May 30, 1968) is a Canadian politician, currently serving as the [[List of premiers of Alberta|18th Premier of Alberta]], serving since 2019, and leader of the [[United Conservative Party]] in [[Alberta]] since 2017. He was the last leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]], before the party's merger with the [[Wildrose Party]] and subsequent dissolution later that year. He was elected the Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] for [[Calgary Lougheed|Calgary-Lougheed]] in a [[by-election]] held on December 14, 2017.\n\nHe previously represented the riding of [[Calgary Midnapore]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] from 1997 until 2016 (known as [[Calgary Southeast]] until 2015). Initially elected as a candidate of the [[Reform Party of Canada]], Kenney was re-elected as a [[Canadian Alliance]] candidate in 2000, and then re-elected four times as the candidate of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]].\n\nFollowing the Conservative victory in the [[2006 Canadian federal election|2006 general election]], Kenney was appointed [[Parliamentary Secretary]] for the [[Prime Minister of Canada]]. On January 4, 2007, he was sworn into the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Privy Council]] as the Secretary of State for [[Multiculturalism]] and Canadian Identity. Kenney held the post of Minister for Citizenship, Immigration and Multiculturalism from October 30, 2008, to July 15, 2013, when he became [[Minister of Families, Children and Social Development|Minister of Employment and Social Development]] and [[Minister of Multiculturalism and Citizenship (Canada)|Minister for Multiculturalism]]. On February 9, 2015, he was named [[Minister of National Defence (Canada)|Minister of National Defence]]. Kenney was considered a [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|potential party leader]] following the defeat of the Conservative government in October 2015 and resignation of Stephen Harper as leader.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/canada-election-2015-chris-hall-harper-succession-1.3278943|title=Stephen Harper is out, here's who might replace him: Chris Hall|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2016, he announced his intention to run for the leadership of the [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]] in that party's [[2017 Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta leadership election|2017 leadership election]].<ref name=\"Jason Kenney urges United Right as he launches Alberta PC Bid\">{{cite news|last1=John|first1=Gibson|title=Jason Kenney urges United Right as he launches Alberta PC Bid|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jason-kenney-alberta-pc-wildrose-leadership-calgary-announcement-1.3666596|website=CBC.ca|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref> Kenney resigned his seat in Parliament on September 23, 2016, after sitting in the House of Commons for 19 years.<ref name=resign/> He was elected leader of the Alberta Progressive Conservatives on March 18, 2017, on a platform of merging with the [[Wildrose Party]], a conservative-minded party active only in Alberta. He served as leader until the merger was effected on July 24, 2017, and was elected United Conservative Party leader on October 28, 2017.\n\nOn April 16, 2019, Kenney successfully led the United Conservative Party to majority government in the [[2019 Alberta general election]], defeating the previous government led by [[Rachel Notley]] of the New Democratic Party with 63 seats and 54.88% of the popular vote and securing only the fifth change of government in Alberta's political history. The [[premiership of Jason Kenney]] began on April 30, 2019 when was sworn in by [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]], [[Lois Mitchell]] forming the [[30th Alberta Legislature]] and becoming the [[List of premiers of Alberta|18th Premier of Alberta]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nKenney was born in [[Oakville, Ontario]], the son of Lynne (n\u00e9e Tunbridge) and Robert Martin Kenney, a fighter pilot and teacher at [[Appleby College]], who was of Irish heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/leaderpost/obituary.aspx?n=martin-kenney&pid=141783748|title=Martin Kenney's Obituary on Leader-Post|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogy.com/ftm/h/u/n/Laurie-Jean-Hunt-BC/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0086.html|title=Laurie-Jean-Hunt-BC - User Trees - Genealogy.com|publisher=}}</ref> He was raised in [[Wilcox, Saskatchewan|Wilcox]], [[Saskatchewan]]. He is the grandson of jazz musician and big band leader [[Mart Kenney]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=2332780&Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=36&Ses=1#LINK87|title=MART KENNEY |date=March 17, 1998|author=Hansard, House of Commons, Canada, 36th Parliament, 1st Session}}</ref>\n\nHe went to high school in [[Wilcox, Saskatchewan]], at the [[Athol Murray College of Notre Dame]], a private Catholic high school, of which his father was president, in 1986.  Kenney also attended [[St. Michaels University School]] in [[Victoria, British Columbia]] from 1982 to 1984.\n\nHe studied [[philosophy]] at the [[University of San Francisco]], a [[Jesuit]] university in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], but failed to complete coursework. During his time in San Francisco, he was interviewed by CNN, for a segment exploring \"religious values\". In the segment, he was credited as \"Jason Kenny \u2013 Anti-abortion Activist\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yhlC-ZrguhA|title=Jason Kenney interviewed by CNN, undated, between 1986-1988}}</ref>  He argued against Jesuit professors, including Rev. John Clarke, who declared free speech essential to a university. Allowing pro-choice activists on campus, Kenney argued in the CNN interview, was \"destroying the mission and the purpose of this university\". In the student newspaper, he suggested that if the school gave a platform to pro-choice groups in the name of free speech, it would have no basis to refuse a similar platform to pedophiles or to the [[Church of Satan]].<ref>{{cite news|author=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Buzzetti |url=https://www.ledevoir.com/politique/canada/320583/des-fous-de-dieu-chez-les-conservateurs |title=Des fous de Dieu chez les conservateurs |newspaper=Le Devoir |date=April 7, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe archbishop rejected the petition that summer, and Kenney never returned to \ufb01nish his undergraduate philosophy degree.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Markusoff |first=Jason |url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/jason-kenney-everything-lose/ |title=Jason Kenney has everything to lose |magazine=Macleans.ca |date=March 6, 2018 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> He left university without graduating to begin work for the [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Douglas|last=Todd|url=http://blogs.vancouversun.com/2010/12/31/jason-kenney-versus-his-own-catholic-church/|title=Jason Kenney versus his own Catholic church|work=The Vancouver Sun|date=December 31, 2010|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> He was \"very involved in the young Liberals\" as a young man, and in 1988 served as executive assistant to [[Ralph Goodale]], who at the time was leader of the [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party|party]].<ref name=\"KeungBlack\">{{cite news|last1=Keung|first1=Nicholas|last2=Black|first2=Debra|title=Q & A: Jason Kenney on his role as Canada\u2019s immigration minister|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/immigration/2013/02/22/q_a_jason_kenney_on_his_role_as_canadas_immigration_minister.html|accessdate=July 20, 2016|work=[[The Toronto Star]]|date=February 22, 2013}}</ref>  Not long after, in 1989, Kenney was hired as the first executive director of the [[Alberta Taxpayers Association]], which advocated for fiscal responsibility. In 1990, Kenney was named president and chief executive officer of the [[Canadian Taxpayers Federation|Canadian Taxpayers]], a self described taxpayers advocacy group that scrutinizes governmental expenditure with a conservative bias.\n\n==In opposition (1997\u20132006)==\n[[File:Jason Kenney (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Kenney at the All Candidates Forum at McKenzie Lake Community Centre in Calgary's Southeast, January 14, 2006]]\nKenney was first elected to the House of Commons in 1997, at the age of 29 as a member of the [[Reform Party of Canada]]. The Reform Party became the [[Canadian Alliance]] (2000\u20132003) and Kenney co-chaired the [[Unite the Right (Canada)|United Alternative]] Task Force. He served as the national co-chairman of [[Stockwell Day]]'s campaign for the leadership of the Canadian Alliance and National Co-Chair of the Canadian Alliance [[2000 Canadian federal election|2000 election campaign]]. While on the Opposition benches from 1997\u20132006, Kenney served in a number of prominent roles in the [[Shadow Cabinet]], including Deputy [[Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons (Canada)|House Leader for the Official Opposition]], critic for [[Canada\u2013United States relations]], critic for National Revenue, and critic for Finance.\n\nKenney supported the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and suggested that the [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien|Chr\u00e9tien]] government's refusal to support the war would damage Canada's relationship with the United States.<ref>Maria Babbage, \"Liberal stance will make it tougher to avoid new border measures, says Alliance\", ''Canadian Press NewsWire'', March 27, 2003.</ref>\n\nKenney was a member of Parliament's Canada\u2013Tibet Committee, and has hosted the [[Dalai Lama XIV|Dalai Lama]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.jasonkenney.ca/EN/4961/62732bn=1 |title = The Honourable Jason Kenney meets with His Holiness the Dalai Lama. |publisher = Jason Kenney |accessdate = February 4, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2005, during a government trade mission in [[China]], Kenney visited the family of recently deceased [[Zhao Ziyang]], the deposed reformist critical of Maoist policies and supportive of free market reforms in China. Zhao, the former [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Premier of China]] and [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary of the Communist Party]], was purged for sympathizing with pro-democracy protesters before they were crushed by the military at [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square in 1989]].\n\n==Parliamentary Secretary to the Prime Minister (2006\u20132007)==\n[[File:KennyOullet&Johnson.jpg|thumb|Kenney, Cardinal [[Marc Ouellet]], and [[David Lloyd Johnston]] at the [[Pontifical Canadian College]] in [[Rome]] in preparation for the inauguration of [[Pope Francis]]]]\nOn February 6, 2006, he was appointed to be [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Stephen Harper]].\n\nIn August 2006, Kenney compared [[Hezbollah]] with the [[Nazi Party]] of 1930s Germany when two opposition MPs suggested taking it off Canada's list of terrorist organizations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/tory-mp-compares-hezbollah-to-nazi-party-1.627252|title=Tory MP compares Hezbollah to Nazi party|last=|first=|date=August 22, 2006|website=|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=July 9, 2016}}</ref> He rebuked [[Prime Minister of Lebanon]] [[Fuad Saniora]] for having criticized Canada, reminding him of the $25 million in reconstructive assistance aid given by Canada to Lebanon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.embassymag.ca/html/index.php?display=story&full_path=/2006/august/23/lebanon/ |title=Re 2006 Israel-Lebanon conflict |publisher=Embassymag.ca |accessdate=June 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090329004031/http://www.embassymag.ca/html/index.php?display=story&full_path=%2F2006%2Faugust%2F23%2Flebanon%2F |archivedate=March 29, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Secretary of State for Multiculturalism and Canadian Identity (2007\u20132008)==\n\nOn January 4, 2007, he was sworn in as the Secretary of State for [[Multiculturalism in Canada|Multiculturalism]] and Canadian Identity, and as a [[Privy councillor (Canada)|Privy Councillor]]. In this capacity, Kenney was the Harper government's representative to ethnic communities in Canada. In this role, Kenney made frequent appearances at ethnic community events across the country, hosted by groups as diverse as Koreans, Ahmadiyya Muslims, Chinese, Jews, Assyrians, South Asians, and Poles. The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' has noted some of the more frequently visited groups in the GTA, which also include the Caribbean community, Persians, Filipinos, and Vietnamese.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/306284bn=1|title = Travelling Tory woos ethnic voters.| newspaper = Toronto Star | accessdate = December 4, 2009|date=February 23, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2008, Kenney posted an announcement on his web site announcing that the Government of Canada recognizes the [[Flag of South Vietnam|flag of the Republic of Vietnam]] as the symbol of the [[Vietnamese-Canadian]] community. He said \"Our government recognises the flag as an important symbol of the Vietnamese-Canadian community's independence, strength, and belief in national unity, and attempts to disparage it are a deeply troubling attack on one of Canada's ethnic communities and on the principles of multiculturalism.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Conservative Party Of Canada |url=http://www.jasonkenney.com/EN/4961/70870 |title=Announcement on Jason Kenney's website re the Republic of Vietnam |publisher=Jasonkenney.com |accessdate=June 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328174023/http://www.jasonkenney.com/EN/4961/70870 |archivedate=March 28, 2009 }}</ref> In May 2008, he made a speech at one of their rallies lending strong support to their program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J_PB6BmTHkQ |title=Speech at ARVN rally |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=June 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, Kenney launched the Community Historical Recognition Program (CHRP) which established 13.5 million dollars in funding over five years for commemorative projects for use by ethno-cultural communities such as the Italian, Jewish, Indian, and Chinese communities that had been the targets of discriminatory Canadian immigration and wartime policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/multiculturalism/programs/community.asp|title=Community Projects|date=June 14, 2016|publisher=[[Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada]]|access-date=July 9, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713061928/http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/multiculturalism/programs/community.asp|archivedate=July 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/welcome-to-my-world/|title=The inside story of Jason Kenney's campaign to win over ethnic votes|last=Castonguay|first=Alec|date=February 2, 2013|magazine=[[Maclean's]]|language=en-US|access-date=July 9, 2016}}</ref> By the project's conclusion in 2013, all the money had been spent except for half a million dollars earmarked for education about the [[Chinese head tax in Canada|Chinese head tax]] was left unspent when one Chinese community group failed to file the required paperwork while others underspent; that money was clawed back into government revenue.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/chinese-head-tax-redress-funds-clawed-back/article9101632/|title=Chinese head-tax redress funds clawed back|last=Friesen|first=Joe|date=February 27, 2013|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|access-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> Because more than thirty other projects involving the Chinese-Canadian community had been funded through the CHRP, Kenney considered the project a success and declined to release the funding, citing the conclusion of the program.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013, Kenney said in his remarks on the end of the CHRP program that the government was \"committed to recognizing and educating Canadians about the experiences of those pioneers who overcame such heavy burdens. Their experiences mark an unfortunate period in our nation\u2019s history. We must ensure that they are never forgotten.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=721119 |title=Archived - Minister Kenney marks achievements of the Canadian Historical Recognition Program (CHRP) |date=February 18, 2013 |publisher=[[Government of Canada]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915034349/http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=721119 |archivedate=September 15, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Minister of Citizenship, Immigration and Multiculturalism (2008\u20132013)==\n[[File:Jason KENNEY ride in the 2010 Calgary, Alberta Stampede Parade.jpg|thumb|Jason Kenney in the 2010 [[Calgary, Alberta]], Stampede Parade]]\nIn 2008, Jason Kenney became [[Minister of Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship|Minister of Citizenship and Immigration]] in Prime Minister Stephen Harper's Cabinet shuffle of October 30, retaining responsibility for multiculturalism, which he had been given in 2007.\n\nIn April 2009, Kenney officially launched [[South Asian Heritage Month|Asian Heritage Month]] to \"better understand the rich diversity the Asian Canadian community brings to Canada\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasonkenney.ca/EN/4961/87677bn=1|title=Minister Jason Kenney launches Asian Heritage Month|date=February 4, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite press_release|title=News Release&nbsp;\u2013 Minister Kenney launches Asian Heritage Month (Ottawa)|date=April 29, 2009|publisher=Citizenship and Immigration Canada|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/releases/2009/2009-04-29.asp|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> Kenney noted that:\n:There were 32 Liberal MPs from the GTA, and of the hundreds of ethnocultural events I attended in the past five years going from [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]] to [[Mississauga]], typically there were no Liberals there&nbsp;... They treated the ethnic communities like passive vote banks owed to them through the supposed myth of [[Pierre Trudeau]]. They mailed it in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/politics/article/987422--exclusive-what-really-sunk-michael-ignatieff-and-the-liberals?bn=1|title=Exclusive: What really sunk Michael Ignatieff and the Liberals|last=Diebel|first=Linda|date=May 7, 2011|work=The Star|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nKenney, speaking in [[Jerusalem]] in December 2009 about Canadian government funding of [[Human rights#Non-governmental Organizations|human rights organizations]], said \"We have de-funded organizations, most recently, like [[KAIROS]] who are taking a leadership role in the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|boycott]] [of Israel]. We're receiving a lot of criticism for these decisions ... but we believe we have done these things for the right reasons, and we stand by these decisions.\" He later added in a letter to the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' that \"While I disagree with the nature of KAIROS's militant stance toward the [[Israel|Jewish homeland]], that is not the reason their request for taxpayer funding was denied.\"<ref>[https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Will+real+Jason+Kenney+please+stand/4805363/story.html#ixzz1ONzG6sl4 Will the real Jason Kenney please stand up?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526224401/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/Will+real+Jason+Kenney+please+stand/4805363/story.html |date=May 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Immigration Minister Jason Kenney blocked any reference to gay rights in a new study guide for immigrants applying for Canadian citizenship. Internal documents show an early draft of the guide contained sections noting that homosexuality was decriminalized in 1969. But Kenney, who fought same-sex marriage when it was debated in Parliament, ordered those key sections removed when his office sent its comments to the department.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beeby |first1=Dean |title=Immigration Minister pulled gay rights from citizenship guide, documents show |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/immigration-minister-pulled-gay-rights-from-citizenship-guide-documents-show/article571718/ |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2010, Kenney announced changes to the Skilled Worker Immigration Program. For their applications to be processed, skilled worker applicants are now required to either have an offer of arranged employment, or be qualified in one of 29 eligible occupations (out of 520 occupations described in the National Occupational Classification (NOC), a standardized framework for organizing information about jobs into a coherent system). A cap of 20,000 applications per year for the skilled workers class was also introduced. As of July 1, 2011, a maximum of 10,000 Federal Skilled Worker applications will be considered for processing in the subsequent 12 months. Within the 10,000 cap, a maximum of 500 federal skilled worker applications per eligible occupation will be considered for processing each year.\n\nKenney said his reform of the immigration point system fixed problems with the previous immigration system. Also, he made the new system more efficient in accepting migrants who could make the best contributions to the Canadian economy. The Canadian Experience Class Program is aiming to attract more international students who qualify as a graduate in the program; and there are two specific requirements to graduate.<ref name=\"Ellliot article\">{{cite news|last=Elliot|first=Louise|title=Kenney's economic immigration changes praised, scorned|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/kenney-s-economic-immigration-changes-praised-scorned-1.1138067|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=October 29, 2015|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> Also, this new program has increased the focus on youth, job skills and most importantly fluent in English or French and at the same time, the immigration department has imposed a new language requirement for Federal  skilled workers (FSW) program.<ref>{{cite web|last=CIC|title=Qualify as a graduate|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/immigrate/cec/graduates.asp|publisher=Citizenship and Immigration Canada|accessdate=October 30, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103173716/http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/immigrate/cec/graduates.asp|archivedate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> One of the new plans is to reduce the processing times and it shows a significant reduction in the wait time. There were cases that had waited for almost a decade to process, but the processing time has been shortened approximately a year period. \"This guarantees no more backlogs\" said by Vancouver immigration lawyer, Richard Kurland.<ref name=\"Ellliot article\"/> However, Kenney decided to delete the backlog of 280,000 skilled worker applications and a lawsuit was held to go against this movement by those applicants, but the lawsuit failed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Immigrant lawsuit fails to preserve backlogged applications|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/immigrant-lawsuit-fails-to-preserve-backlogged-applications-1.1205232|publisher=The Canadian Press|accessdate=October 29, 2012|date=May 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhile Immigration Minister, Kenney asserted that the generosity of the immigration system was not to be abused. \"I held town hall meetings across the country to hear from victims of marriage fraud. In addition to the heartbreak and pain that came from being lied to and deceived, these people were angry. They felt they had been used as a way to get to Canada. We are taking action because immigration to Canada should not be built upon deceit.\" said Minister Kenney<ref>{{cite web|title=Minister Kenney introduces sponsorship restriction to address marriage fraud|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/releases/2012/2012-03-02.asp|publisher=CIC|accessdate=October 30, 2012}}</ref> The Protecting Canada's Immigration System Act has been published to protect and fix Canada's immigration system. While Minister, Kenney focused on major issues such as fraud marriage, human smugglers, unfounded refugees, and the billion-dollar bill of health and social benefits claimed from them. It is estimated that the provinces are to save approximately $1.65 billion from their social assistance and education sector over five years with the Balanced Refugee Reform Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legislation to Protect Canada's Immigration System Receives Royal Assent|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/releases/2012/2012-06-29.asp|publisher=CIC|accessdate=October 30, 2012}}</ref> This would be a few dollars per Canadian per year in tax saved (population of Canada 34 million) [[Population of Canada by year]]. Also, a five-year sponsorship bar is published, which means sponsored spouses or partners are to wait five years from the day they received permanent residence status in Canada to sponsor a new spouse or partner. Furthermore, Minister Kenney claimed that these new measures are making an easier law enforcement and stiffer penalties to prosecute human smugglers and  a message to human smugglers and they will not be able to abuse Canada's generosity anymore.\n\nThere has been significant criticism of the institution of a Designated Country of Origin (DCO) list which attributes countries as being unlikely to persecute. Therefore, refugee claimants coming from these countries (included are Hungary, Mexico, and Israel) will undergo a different refugee claimant process.<ref>{{cite web|title=Designated Country of Origin List|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/refugees/reform-safe.asp|publisher=Canadian Government|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> Furthermore, refugee claimants from countries on the DCO no longer receive emergency healthcare coverage.\n\nIn 2011, he imposed a ban on [[niqab]] face veils for those taking the oath of citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/americas/2015/09/16/woman-wins-niqab-ban-appeal-in-court-against-canadian-state|title=Woman wins niqab-ban appeal in court against Canadian state|publisher=}}</ref> In his appeal on behalf of [[Minister of Citizenship and Immigration|Department of Citizenship and Immigration]] in Citizenship and Immigration v Ishaq, 2015 FCA 194, the three justices ruled in favour of [[Zunera Ishaq]] and her right to wear the niqab confirming that the federal requirement was unlawful.<ref name=\"Federal Court of Appeal\">{{cite web | url=http://decisions.fca-caf.gc.ca/fca-caf/decisions/en/120099/1/document.do |title=Canada (Citizenship and Immigration) v Ishaq, 2015 FCA 194| publisher=Federal Court of Appeal | date=October 5, 2015 | accessdate=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"macleans_Wherry\">{{citation | url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/the-one-sentence-that-sums-up-the-niqab-debate/ | title=The one sentence that sums up the niqab 'debate:' Nestled in Justice Johanne Trudel\u2019s 24-paragraph Federal Court of Appeal decision is a phrase that explains this whole sorry mess| publisher=Macleans | date=October 7, 2015 | accessdate=October 9, 2015 | author=Wherry, Aaron}}</ref>\n\nAlong with [[Rona Ambrose]], Minister for the Status of Women, Kenney was one of ten cabinet ministers who decided to vote in favour of a motion to study when life begins.<ref name=\"The Globe and Mail\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/ndp-slams-jason-kenney-for-supporting-abortion-debate/article4566487/|title=The Globe and Mail&nbsp;\u2014 NDP slams Jason Kenney for supporting \u2018abortion\u2019 debate|last=Hannay|first=Chris|date=September 25, 2012|work=The Globe and Mail|location=Toronto|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Investigations into citizenship fraud===\nOn July 19, 2011, Kenney announced that the government intends to revoke the citizenship of 1,800 people it believes obtained their status through fraudulent means. The decision to revoke Canadian citizenship is rare, and a large-scale proposed crackdown had no precedent. Fewer than 70 citizenships have been revoked since the [[Canadian Citizenship Act 1946|1946 Citizenship Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/story/2011/07/20/pol-kenney-immigration-visas.html|title=Ottawa targets 1,800 in citizenship crackdown|work=[[CBC News]]|date=July 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn investigation into residence fraud continues to grow and almost 11,000 cases are being reviewed. Recently, [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada]] (CIC) has revoked up to 3,100 citizens' citizenship because they have cheated or lied to become a Canadian citizen. \"Canadian citizenship is not for sale and we are taking action to strip citizenship and permanent residence status from people who do not play by rules\", said by Minister Kenney.<ref name=\"Citizenship and Immigration Canada\">{{cite web|title=Canadian citizenship not for sale: Minister Kenney provides update on residence fraud investigations|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/releases/2012/2012-09-10.asp|publisher=Citizenship and Immigration Canada|accessdate=November 1, 2012}}</ref> Also, CIC works inseparably with the Canada Border Services Agency (CBSA), the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) and Canadian offices overseas to solve the fraud. \"These efforts reinforce our government\u2019s commitment to protecting the integrity of our immigration system,\" said Canada's Public Safety Minister Vic Toews. It is believed that about 5,000 people who have Canadian permanent status are outside of Canada and implicated in residence fraud.<ref name=\"Citizenship and Immigration Canada\"/>\n\nIn January 2009, Kenney made public statements critical of [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters|U.S. soldiers seeking asylum in Canada]] who were facing punishment for their refusal to participate in the Iraq war. He said that unlike in the Vietnam era, the current asylum seekers are neither \"[[draft dodger]]s\" nor \"[[List of Iraq War Resisters|resisters]]\", but rather are \"people who volunteer to serve in the armed forces of a democratic country and simply change their mind to desert. And that's fine, that's the decision they have made, but they are not refugees.\" He also said that he considered them to be \"bogus refugee claimants\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kenney-s-comments-prejudice-hearings-for-war-resisters-critics-say-1.781908 |title=Kenney's comments prejudice hearings for war resisters, critics say |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=January 9, 2009 |accessdate=May 26, 2015 }}</ref> These remarks have been seen by some supporters of the asylum seekers as being a form of interference in the asylum process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wmtc.blogspot.com/2008/12/jason-kenney-admits-interfering-in-war.html |title='&#39;We move to Canada blog'&#39; |publisher=Wmtc.blogspot.com |date=December 30, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/January2009/09/c6310.html |title='&#39;Canadian News Wire'&#39; \"Open Letter to Minister Jason Kenney from Canadian Council for Refugees re: War Resisters\" |publisher=Newswire.ca |date= |accessdate=June 5, 2010}}</ref> He believed that [[Kimberly Rivera]], an American soldier seeking refuge was not a legitimate refugee.  \"Military deserters from the United States are not genuine refugees under the internationally accepted meaning of the term,\" said Alexis Pavlich, the minister's press secretary.<ref name=\"The Canadian Press\">{{cite web|last=Siu|first=Michelle|title=The Canadian Press&nbsp;\u2014 American war resister considering deportation appeal|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/american-war-resister-considering-deportation-appeal-1.937746|work=The Canadian Press|publisher=The Canadian Press|accessdate=September 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Admissibility decisions===\nAs part of Kenney's ''Faster Removal of Foreign Criminals Act'', introduced in June 2012, the Minister of Citizenship, Immigration and Multiculturalism would have the ability to deny entry to Canada based on \"public police considerations. He was quoted in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' saying that present immigration laws do not allow someone to be kept out if they are seeking to promote violence. The previous year, both the official opposition [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] (NDP) and Quebec's National Assembly had asked Kenney to exercise negative discretion but no such ability existed under Canadian law.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kenney seeks power to bar people from entering Canada for \u2018public-policy considerations\u2019 |author=Cambell Clark |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/kenney-seeks-power-to-bar-people-from-entering-canada-for-public-policy-considerations/article4617304// |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=October 16, 2012 |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |location=Toronto}}</ref> During debate in the House of Commons, the NDP criticized this component of the bill, arguing it gives too much power to the minister.<ref>{{cite news |title=Immigration minister to give criteria for denying entry to Canada\u2019 |author=Laura Payton |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/immigration-minister-to-give-criteria-for-denying-entry-to-canada-1.1239681 |newspaper=[[CBC News]] |date=October 16, 2012 |accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, in March 2009, the [[Canada Border Services Agency]] prevented British politician [[George Galloway]] from entering Canada, where he had planned to give a series of speeches against the [[war in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How George Galloway was barred from Canada in less than 2 hours |author=Cambell Clark |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/how-george-galloway-was-barred-from-canada-in-less-than-2-hours/article4096622/ |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=October 10, 2012 |location=Toronto}}</ref> The Immigration Minister's Office stated that the Canada Border Services Agency deemed Galloway as inadmissible to Canada due to national security concerns. Galloway had openly given what he called \"financial support\" to [[Hamas]], classified as a terrorist group in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/605682 |title=Canada blocks outspoken British MP |publisher=thestar.com |date= March 20, 2009|accessdate=June 5, 2010 | location=Toronto | first1=Richard J. | last1=Brennan | first2=Allan | last2=Woods}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Deborah Summers and agencies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/mar/20/george-galloway-banned-canada |title='&#39;The Guardian UK'&#39;:\"George Galloway banned from Canada\" |newspaper=The Guardian |date= March 20, 2009|accessdate=June 5, 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nGalloway pursued the matter in the Canadian court system, where it was revealed that Kenney's office had emailed the CBSA on the matter. The [[Federal Court (Canada)|Federal Court]] found that Kenney's office had used \"a flawed and overreaching interpretation of the standards under Canadian law for labeling someone as engaging in terrorism or being a member of a terrorist organization.\" The presiding judge also determined that the [[Canada Border Services Agency]] had produced its assessment of Galloway on scant evidence after receiving instructions from Kenney's staff,<ref>{{cite news|author=Alison Crawford |url=http://www.cbc.ca/politics/story/2010/09/27/mp-galloway-banned-kenney-fed-court.html |title=Galloway's Canada ban won't be reviewed |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date= September 27, 2010|accessdate=October 12, 2010 | location=Toronto}}</ref> who attempted to bar Galloway because \"they disagreed with his political views\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Alison Crawford |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2010/10/02/galloway-canada.html |title=Galloway allowed into Canada |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date= October 2, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2012 | location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n''The Globe and Mail'' later pointed out that while Kenney was quick to refuse Galloway entry into Canada, his department gave entry to controversial politician [[Geert Wilders]], who has compared [[Islam]] to [[Fascism]] and campaigned to ban the [[Quran]] from the [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://m.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/why-is-national-arts-centre-hosting-dutch-mp-accused-of-being-anti-islam/article2016836/?service=mobile |title=Why is National Arts Centre hosting Dutch MP accused of being anti-Islam? |work=The Globe and Mail |date=May 10, 2011 |first=Gloria |last=Galloway |access-date=July 25, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313073215/http://m.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/why-is-national-arts-centre-hosting-dutch-mp-accused-of-being-anti-islam/article2016836/?service=mobile |archive-date=March 13, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Wilders spoke in Toronto and Ottawa, generating further controversy.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.nationalpost.com/2011/05/05/anti-islamic-political-leader-geert-wilders-comes-to-canada/ |title=Anti-Islamic political leader Geert Wilders comes to Canada |work=[[The National Post]] |date=May 5, 2011 |first=Jessica |last=Hume}}</ref>\n\n===Citizenship policy changes===\n[[File:Jason Kenney's speech at Black April demonstration, Apr-30-12.jpg|thumb|300px|Jason Kenney's speech at [[Fall of Saigon|Black April]] demonstration]]\nA new law amending the [[Canadian Citizenship Act 1946|Citizenship Act]] came into effect on April 17, 2009. One of the changes instituted by the Government of Canada is the \"first generation limitation\", considered a punitive measure by some against naturalized citizens who reside abroad for lengthy periods of time.{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} Minister Kenney said the following in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] on June 10, 2010: \"That's why we must protect the values of Canadian citizenship and must take steps against those who would cheapen it&nbsp;... We will strengthen the new limitation on the ability to acquire citizenship for the second generation born abroad.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/speeches/2010/2010-06-10.asp |title=Speaking notes for The Honourable Jason Kenney, P.C., M.P. Minister of Citizenship, Immigration and Multiculturalism to announce legislation regarding citizenship |date=June 10, 2010 |access-date=January 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222213321/http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/speeches/2010/2010-06-10.asp |archive-date=December 22, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nThe new rules would not confer a Canadian citizenship on children born outside of Canada to parents who were also born outside of Canada. Thus for children to obtain Canadian citizenship if born abroad, they would have to have one parent who was born in Canada. Another effect of this law was to abolish automatic Citizenship by birth for the children of parents in Canada in the service of a foreign government. Children born to foreign diplomats in Canada would only become Canadian if at least one parent was either a Canadian citizen or a Permanent Resident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/citizenship/rules.asp#understand |title=Changes to citizenship rules as of April 2009 |access-date=April 20, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420015439/http://www.cic.gc.ca/ENGLISH/citizenship/rules.asp#understand |archive-date=April 20, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kenney introduced ''Discover Canada'', a new citizenship guide for prospective citizens. ''[[The Canadian Press]]'' reported that Kenney blocked information about [[same-sex marriage]] from the Citizenship and Immigration study guide for immigrants applying for citizenship,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/773841--kenney-blocked-gay-rights-in-citizenship-guide-documents?bn=1|title=Kenney blocked gay rights in citizenship guide: documents|date=March 2, 2010 | work=The Star | first=Dean | last=Beeby | accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> although a sentence was included in a 2011 revision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/citizenship-guide-gets-single-sentence-on-gay-rights-1.618396 |title=Citizenship guide gets single sentence on gay rights |date=March 14, 2011 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref> The revised edition also added information about arts and culture, the War of 1812, and an admonition against importing \"violent, extreme or hateful prejudices\" to Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/releases/2011/2011-03-14a.asp |date=March 14, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217131225/http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/department/media/releases/2011/2011-03-14a.asp |archivedate=December 17, 2013 |title=News Release&nbsp;\u2014 Updated Discover Canada citizenship study guide now available |publisher=Citizenship and Immigration Canada}}</ref>\n\nKenney has taken steps to restore full citizenship status to the \"Lost Canadians\", Canadian nationals who had \"fallen through the cracks\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.articlealley.com/article_530746_18.html |title= Immigration Dept rejoices as \"Lost Canadians\" citizenship bill is passed |date=May 7, 2008|author= Robert Palmer }}</ref> Bill C-37 corrected the citizenship issues for 95% of \"Lost Canadians\" and special grants were to have been made to resolve the remaining 5%. Kenney says the Lost Canadians group should not be politicizing their plight but they should be making a \"solid application and a strong case\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=smjrQPLeWkU|title=Still Lost Canadians Protest|date=October 22, 2009|author=Terry Milewski}}</ref>  Kenney's predecessor, [[Diane Finley]], had authorized a special grant of citizenship to Guy Valliere, although he died prior to receiving citizenship.\n\n===Refugee reform===\n[[File:Jason Kenney and Ngo Thanh Hai with Members of Committee To Support Victims of Communism.jpg|thumb|300px|Jason Kenney and Senator [[Thanh Hai Ngo]] with Members of Committee To Support Victims of Communism]]\nOn March 29, 2010, Kenney announced an overhaul of the [[Canadian refugee system]]. The reform package also committed to allowing the resettlement of 2,500 more refugees living in UN refugee camps and urban slums.<ref name=\"jasonkenney1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jasonkenney.com/EN/4961/109603|title=Expanding Canada's Refugee Resettlement Programs|date=April 28, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510073044/http://www.jasonkenney.com/EN/4961/109603|archivedate=May 10, 2010}}</ref> The plan also included expansion of the Government-Assisted Refugees Program to 500 places while a further 2,000 resettlement places were added to the [[Private Sponsorship of Refugees Program]].<ref name=\"jasonkenney1\"/>  In total, the new plan would lead to the resettlement of 14,500 UN-selected refugees from refugee camps and urban slums to Canada.<ref name=\"jasonkenney1\"/>\n\n\"[[Protecting Canada's Immigration System Act]]\", or Bill C-31, \"An Act to amend the [[Immigration and Refugee Protection Act]] and other acts\", was introduced on February 16, 2012, and received [[Royal Assent]] on June 28, 2012. It has been broadly criticized as it \"gives Ministers broad, unfettered and unprecedented powers\" among other new powers. It was sponsored by Kenney.\n\nThere has been significant controversy around changes to the social assistance program for refugee claimants (Interim Federal Health).<ref>{{cite news |title=Doctors plead for cuts to refugee health to be reversed |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/doctors-plead-for-cuts-to-refugee-health-coverage-to-be-reversed/article12626378 |work= The Globe and Mail |access-date= July 17, 2013 |location=Toronto |date= June 17, 2013}}</ref> Physicians and allied health professionals have opposed these cuts through national protests in all major cities in Canada.<ref name=\"Canadian Doctors for Refugee Health Care\">{{cite web|title=Canadian Doctors for Refugee Health Care |url= http://www.doctorsforrefugeecare.ca/day-of-action-june-17-2013.html |work=Physicians |accessdate=July 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018122152/http://www.doctorsforrefugeecare.ca/day-of-action-june-17-2013.html |archivedate= October 18, 2013}}</ref>  Physicians opposing the cuts to refugee health care include [[Vincent Lam]] who stated that Canada is a country known for its tolerance and diversity, but we [healthcare professionals] are \"dismayed and ashamed at the cuts for healthcare for refugees\" <ref name=Youtube>{{cite web|last=Sheppard|first=Graham|title=Video of Day of Action against Refugee Health Care Cuts|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JXr1cL8yHdQ#at=50|accessdate=July 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfghan interpreters who served alongside Canadian troops in southern Afghanistan and who applied for Canadian visas on the basis of facing threats from insurgents were denied visas. Kenney backed this decision.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/article/1088278--kenney-backs-bureaucrats-who-denied-visa-for-afghan-interpreter|title=Kenney backs bureaucrats who denied visa for Afghan interpreter|date=November 16, 2011 | work=The Star|location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\nKenney promised that Canada would resettle more refugees from 2011\u20132012 than in previous years. Instead, there was a 26% drop in refugee resettlement in Canada during that period, hitting a 30-year low. [[Loly Rico]], president of the [[Canadian Council for Refugees]], criticized Kenny for not following through on his promise.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[International Business Times]]|title=Canada Witnesses Dramatic Drop In Resettled Refugees Despite Pledge to Grant More Asylum|date=March 8, 2013|url=http://ca.ibtimes.com/articles/443807/20130308/canada-refugee-council.htm|accessdate=November 14, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420030024/http://ca.ibtimes.com/articles/443807/20130308/canada-refugee-council.htm|archivedate=April 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage fraud===\nResponding to feedback in townhalls and public consultations, Kenney took steps in 2012<ref>{{cite web|title = Jason Kenney announces tougher immigration restrictions for newlyweds to combat marriage fraud|url = http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/jason-kenney-announces-tougher-immigration-restrictions-for-newlyweds-to-combat-marriage-fraud|accessdate = August 20, 2015}}</ref> to fight against [[Sham marriage|marriage fraud]]. Many cases had arisen in which Canadians had been taken advantage of by would-be spouses simply to facilitate their entry into Canada. These Canadian victims' trust in their supposed husband or wife was violated for fraudulent immigration purposes. Once status was acquired in Canada the prospective spouse would leave the Canadian spouse who had sponsored him in, revealing their marriage to have been a lie. Kenney instituted a five-year bar or prohibition on spousal sponsorship for those who had already been sponsored by a spouse into Canada.<ref name=\"Immigration Fraud: Jason Kenney warns of marriages of convenience\">{{cite web|title=\"Immigration Fraud: Jason Kenney warns of \"marriage of convenience\"|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/03/20/jason-kenney-marriage-fraud_n_2917029.html|website=huffingtonpost.ca|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=July 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nKenney also implemented a conditional permanent residency status to ensure that a spouse or partner had to live as husband and wife for a minimum of two years with their Canadian sponsor-spouse, or else they would have their status revoked. The anti-fraud measures were designed to protect Canadian victims as well as crack down on those who collaborated with fraudulent sponsored spouses for monetary gain.<ref name=\"Ottawa moves to curb marriages of convenience\">{{cite news|last1=Bill|first1=Curry|title=Ottawa moves to curb marriages of convenience|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-moves-to-curb-marriages-of-convenience/article4182749/|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Sun News citizenship ceremony===\nDuring the fall of 2011, Jason Kenney's office had Department of Immigration officials organize a citizenship ceremony for [[Sun News Network]]. Later it became known that some of the participants were ministerial staff reaffirming citizenship, rather than new Canadian citizens. Jason Kenney's office and Sun News Media initially claimed to have no knowledge of this incident and blamed well-meaning civil servants.  Internal correspondence revealed through access to information laws later revealed that both Sun News and Jason Kenney's staff in fact made the decision to proceed with ministerial staff in the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/officials-contradict-kenney-on-sun-role-in-fake-citizenship-ceremony/article4231322/ | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Officials contradict Kenney on Sun role in fake citizenship ceremony | date=June 5, 2012 | location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/jason-kenney-tory-officials-split-on-details-of-sun-news-network-fake-citizenship-ceremony|title=Jason Kenney, Tory officials split on details of Sun News Network \u2018fake citizenship\u2019 ceremony|work=National Post|date=June 5, 2012|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/fake-sun-tv-citizenship-ceremony-explanations-in-dispute-1.1194696|title=Fake Sun TV citizenship ceremony explanations in dispute|last=|first=|date=June 5, 2012|work=[[CBC News]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|access-date=July 8, 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Office of Religious Freedom===\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi and the Prime Minister of Canada, Mr. Stephen Harper at the Gurudwara Khalsa Diwan, at Ross Street, Vancouver, in Canada on April 16, 2015 (1).jpg|thumb|Kenney with [[Stephen Harper]] and [[Narendra Modi]] at a [[gurdwara]] in Vancouver]]\nFollowing up on a Conservative campaign promise from the [[2011 Canadian federal election]], Kenney initiated the creation of the [[Office of Religious Freedom (Canada)|Office of Religious Freedom]], an agency of [[Foreign Affairs Canada]], to monitor [[religious oppression]] domestically and promote [[religious freedom]] internationally.<ref name=\"Ottawa Citizen\">{{cite web|last1=Berthiaume|first1=Lee|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/politics/faith-groups-call-on-liberals-to-keep-office-of-religious-freedom |title=Faith groups call on Liberals to keep Office of Religious Freedom |date=January 22, 2016 |accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref> Former British Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] endorsed the office in a visit to Canada in 2013, saying, \"I think it shows leadership from Canada. And Canada, by the way, in many ways is a perfect place from which to promote this ideal because of the complexion of the country.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blanchfield |first1=Mike |title=Tony Blair lauds feds' Office of Religious Freedom |url=https://ipolitics.ca/2013/10/23/blair-lauds-feds-office-of-religious-freedom/ |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |work=iPolitics |date=October 23, 2013}}</ref> The Liberal government which formed after the [[2015 Canadian federal election]] closed the office in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Evan|first1=Solomon|title=In defense of the office of religious freedom|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/in-defence-of-the-defunct-office-of-religious-freedom/|website=macleans.ca|publisher=Maclean's Magazine|accessdate=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Minister of Employment and Social Development (2013\u20132015)==\nAs part of the July 2013 cabinet shuffle, Kenney was named Minister of Employment and Social Development, a post he held simultaneously with his role as Minister of National Defence. While Minister of Employment, Kenney focused on expediting the review process for [[Canada Pension Plan]] and Old Age Security disability appeals, which had become backlogged under the previous tribunal process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2014/11/27/large_social_security_backlog_unacceptable_kenney_says.html|title=Large social security backlog unacceptable, Kenney says {{!}} Toronto Star|website=thestar.com|access-date=July 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKenney reached an agreement with provincial and territorial counterparts\u2014except Quebec\u2014to implement the [[Canada Job Grant]], which aims to train unemployed workers who do not qualify for [[Unemployment benefits|employment insurance]], over the next four years in January 2014.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/canada-job-grant-notably-different-from-take-it-or-leave-it-offer-1.2555173|title=Canada Job Grant notably different from take it or leave it offer|last=Mas|first=Susana|date=February 28, 2014|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=July 8, 2016|via=}}</ref> The final agreement provided more flexibility for the provinces and territories than in the initial proposal in 2013, which had been rejected by all Kenney's counterparts for its \"take it or leave it\" nature \u2013 potentially forcing the provincial and territories to forgo $300 million of the $500 million in federal funding provided to them by Labour Market Agreements if they did not accept the plan.<ref name=\":0\" /> Two and a half million dollars were spent on ads for the program during expensive [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] television spots in 2013 and 2014, even before the details of the federal-provincial agreements were finalized or approved, which prompted [[Advertising Standards Canada]] to label them as \"misleading\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/canada-job-grant-ads-cost-2-5m-for-non-existent-program-1.2495196|title=Canada Job Grant ads cost $2.5M for non-existent program|last=Harris|first=Sophia|date=January 13, 2014|work=[[CBC News]]|access-date=July 8, 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/ads-tout-job-grants-program-that-doesn-t-yet-exist-1.1319341|title=Ads tout job grants program that doesn't yet exist|last=|first=|date=May 19, 2013|work=[[CBC News]]|agency=[[The Canadian Press]]|access-date=July 8, 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Minister of Defence (2015)==\n[[File:U.S. Secretary of Defense Ash Carter meets Canadian Minister of National Defense Jason Kenney at NATO Headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.jpg|thumb|Canadian Minister of National Defense Jason Kenney meets U.S. Secretary of Defense [[Ash Carter]] at [[NATO]] Headquarters in [[Brussels, Belgium]]]]\nIn February 2015, Kenney was promoted to Minister of Defence after a cabinet shuffle in which Foreign Minister [[John Baird (Canadian politician)|John Baird]] left federal politics, and former Defence Minister [[Rob Nicholson]] became Foreign Minister.<ref name=\"Cabinet shuffle\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2015/02/09/conservative-cabinet-shuffle-makes-jason-kenney-defence-minister.html | title=Jason Kenney new defence minister in Conservative cabinet shuffle | newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] | date=February 9, 2015 | accessdate=September 17, 2015 | author=Boutilier, Alex}}</ref> While Minister of Defense, Kenney took a hard-line approach to security, saying it was necessary for Canada to fight against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] militants to prevent them from becoming a threat to Canada.<ref name=\"India born former soldier sworn in as Canada's new defense minister\">{{cite web|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idCAKCN0ST2LV20151104|title=India-born former soldier sworn in as Canada's new defense minister|last=Schnurr|first=Leah|date=November 4, 2015|website=Reuters.ca|publisher=Reuters|access-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-March 2015, Kenney claimed that Russian warships had confronted ships of the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and that Russian fighters had [[buzzed]] {{HMCS|Fredericton}} at low altitude while it participated in a NATO maritime task force off the coast of [[Ukraine]] as part of a mission against [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian intervention]] in the country.<ref name=\"NATO Kenney\">{{cite news | url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/dnd-russian-confrontation-claims | title=NATO officials contradict Jason Kenney\u2019s claim that Russian fighter jets flew over Canadian navy frigate | newspaper=[[National Post]] | date=March 14, 2015 | accessdate=September 17, 2015 | author=Pugliese, David}}</ref> NATO officials later stated that Russian ships could be seen on the horizon, but never approached the NATO fleet and that all flyovers of the fleet by Russian planes had been at high altitudes.<ref name=\"NATO Kenney\" />\n\nIn late March 2015, Kenney defended the Canadian airstrike campaign against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] being extended into Syria by claiming that it was necessary because among the coalition air forces, only the Canadians and Americans had planes capable of using [[precision guided munitions]], when in fact, Arab allies such as [[Saudi Arabia]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]] had won praise from General [[Martin Dempsey]], the Chairman of the US Joint Chiefs of Staff for their use of precision guided munitions.<ref name=\"Lawson crater\">{{cite news | url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/gen-tom-lawson-tries-to-dig-jason-kenney-out-of-a-bomb-crater-of-his-own-making | title=Gen. Tom Lawson tries to dig Jason Kenney out of a bomb crater of his own making | newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]] | date=March 30, 2015 | accessdate=September 17, 2015 | author=Pugliese, David}}</ref> General [[Thomas J. Lawson|Tom Lawson]], then Chief of Canada's Defence Staff, issued a statement defending Kenney's statement, but later retracted it and apologized, saying that its contents were incorrect.<ref name=\"About face\">{{cite news | url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/about-face-as-canadas-top-general-admits-letter-backing-jason-kenney-on-smart-missiles-is-incorrect | title=About-face as Canada\u2019s top general admits letter backing Jason Kenney on smart missiles is incorrect | newspaper=[[National Post]] | date=April 1, 2015 | accessdate=September 17, 2015 | author=Pugliese, David}}</ref> Sources within the Department of Defence say that Lawson had been pressured into releasing the inaccurate statement by Kenney's office.<ref name=\"About face\" />\n\nAlso in March 2015, Kenney faced criticism for tweeting photos purporting to be of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] enslaving girls. One of the images was taken years before ISIS came into existence and appeared to be from an [[Day of Ashura|Ashura]] procession; another turned out to be a picture staged in [[London, England]], by actors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/politics/the-gargoyle-kenney-tweets-misleading-photos-of-muslim-women-in-chains|title=The Gargoyle \u2013 Kenney tweets misleading photos of Muslim women in chains|date=March 10, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Kenney announced that troops from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] would be sent to Ukraine as trainers for Ukrainian forces as part of Operation UNIFIER. The soldiers, who arrived in September 2015, were from [[2 Canadian Mechanized Brigade Group]] (2 CMBG) and were stationed in at the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine|Ukrainian Armed Forces]] [[:w:uk:\u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u0437\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0438|International Peacekeeping and Security Centre]] near the Polish-Ukrainian border at [[Yavoriv]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/09/01/canadian-soldiers-land-in-ukraine-for-training-mission|title=Canadian soldiers land in Ukraine for training mission|last=Warmington|first=Joe|date=September 1, 2015|website=[[Toronto Sun]]|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]|access-date=July 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, after a report was published on sexual misconduct in the [[Canadian Forces]], Kenney promised that an independent centre at arm's length from the military would be formed to hear complaints of sexual misconduct in the military and provide support and resources for victims.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jason-kenney-guarantees-independent-centre-to-handle-military-sexual-misconduct-1.3072324 | title=Jason Kenney guarantees independent centre to handle military sexual misconduct | publisher=[[CBC News]] | date=May 13, 2015 | accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Role in the Conservative Party==\n\nKenney was widely recognized for his central role in the Conservative Party's successful 2011 election campaign, reaching out to ethnic minority voters, and the Conservative parliamentary majority that resulted.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/how-courting-the-immigrant-vote-paid-off-for-the-tories/article578608/ |title=How courting the immigrant vote paid off for the Tories |publisher=theglobeandmail.com |date=May 3, 2011 |accessdate=March 23, 2013 |location=Toronto}}</ref> He has acknowledged publicly that his ongoing strategy of promoting conservative values and policies in government so as to capture the support of ethnic communities has been in the works since years prior to Stephen Harper first winning government in 2006.<ref name=\":2\" /> Kenney has also suggested that Stephen Harper was one of the first people he consulted with on the ethnic outreach strategy when the latter was still an opposition [[Canadian Alliance]] MP.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jasonkenney.ca/news/minister-jason-kenneys-speech-at-the-opening-ceremonies-of-the-conservative-convention-june-9-201/ |title=Jason Kenney's 2011 Conservative Convention speech |publisher=jasonkenney.ca |date=June 9, 2011 |accessdate=March 23, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927223324/http://www.jasonkenney.ca/news/minister-jason-kenneys-speech-at-the-opening-ceremonies-of-the-conservative-convention-june-9-201/ |archivedate=September 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nKenney's ethnic outreach strategy was also evident when in early 2011, a letter using government stationery was sent to Conservative riding associations seeking assistance in raising $200,000 funding for an ad campaign aimed at bolstering support among ethnic communities in ridings that the Conservatives are targeting in the next election.<ref name=free>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/03/pol-kenney-letter.html |title=Kenney fundraising letter breaks rules: NDP |publisher=CBC.ca |date=March 3, 2011 |accessdate=March 3, 2011}}</ref>  News of this broke when a copy was believed to have been mistakenly sent to the office of opposition MP [[Linda Duncan]] instead of that of fellow Conservative MP [[John Duncan (Canadian politician)|John Duncan]] (no relation). This led to criticism over the letter's labelling of certain groups and ridings as \"ethnic\" or \"very ethnic\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/04/pol-kenney-letter-reax.html |title=Ethnic voter plan is 'offensive': Liberals |publisher=CBC.ca |date=March 4, 2011 |accessdate=April 15, 2011}}</ref> Kenney publicly apologized for the mailing error, citing a staffer's inexperience as the explanation.\n\nAs Immigration Minister, Kenney has been largely credited with building bridges attracting ethnic communities to the Conservative Party, which was long dominated by the Liberal Party. In addition, he also handled the apology and financial compensation for the Chinese head tax and the official recognition of the Armenian and Ukrainian genocides.  According to an observer, \"He acts as a conductor to correct historical wrongs, It might not seem important to the majority of the population, but for the concerned communities, it\u2019s huge.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2011/05/07/exclusive_what_really_sunk_michael_ignatieff_and_the_liberals.html|title=Exclusive: What really sunk Michael Ignatieff and the Liberals|date=May 7, 2011|work=The Star|location=Toronto}}</ref> According to ''The Globe and Mail'', the Chinese-Canadian community nicknamed Kenney the \"Smiling Buddha\" in reference to his efforts to garner ethnic votes on the basis of what some perceive as commonly held conservative values.<ref name=\"Friesen article\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/the-smiling-buddha-and-his-multicultural-charms/article4388303/?page=all|title=Jason Kenney: The 'Smiling Buddha' and his multicultural charms|last=Friesen|first=Joe|date=January 29, 2010|work=The Globe and Mail|location=Toronto|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> The ''Toronto Star'' characterized him as having a \"[[Bieber]]-like\" following in many communities.<ref name=\"&amp;quot;Kenney attracts bieber-like following in ethnic communities&amp;quot;\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/immigration/2013/02/22/jason_kenney_attracts_bieberlike_following_in_ethnic_communities.html|title=Jason Kenney attracts 'Bieber-like' following in ethnic communities|last=Black|first=Debra|last2=Keung|first2=Nicholas|date=February 22, 2013|work=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> Kenney justified his efforts to gain ethnic support by stating:\n:You observe how these new Canadians live their lives. They are the personification of [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s aspirational class. They're all about a massive work ethic.<ref name=\"Friesen article\" />\n\n==Return to opposition and provincial leadership candidacy==\nThe Conservatives were defeated at [[2015 Canadian federal election|the 2015 Canadian federal election]], though Kenney was reelected in [[Calgary Midnapore]], essentially a reconfigured version of his old riding. Kenney was named to the [[House of Commons of Canada Special Committee on Electoral Reform|Special Committee on Electoral Reform]]. Kenney was long considered a likely candidate to succeed Stephen Harper as leader of the Conservative Party of Canada and had been mentioned as a prospective candidate and presumed frontrunner in the [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|next leadership election]] to be held in 2017,<ref name=\"ch\">{{cite news|title=Election results promise repercussions for all party leaders|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/opinion/1317345-howe-room-election-results-promise-repercussions-for-all-party-leaders|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=Chronicle-Herald|date=October 18, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"who\">{{cite news|title=Who will replace Steven Harper as leader of the Conservatives?|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/who-will-replace-steven-harper-as-leader-of-the-progressive-conservatives|accessdate=October 20, 2015|work=National Post|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> His name has also been mentioned as a prospective leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Alberta]] who could potentially unite the rival Progressive Conservative and [[Wildrose Party|Wildrose]] parties.<ref>{{cite news|title=The dozen who will dominate politics in 2016|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/01/01/the-dozen-who-will-dominate-politics-in-2016-tim-harper.html|accessdate=January 8, 2016|work=Toronto Star|date=January 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Why nobody\u2019s going to be \u2018uniting the right\u2019 in Alberta any time soon|url=https://ipolitics.ca/2016/01/07/why-nobodys-going-to-be-uniting-the-right-in-alberta-any-time-soon/|accessdate=January 8, 2016|work=iPolitics|date=January 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tony Clement organizers meet to discuss possible leadership bid|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2015/12/12/tony-clement-organizers-meet-to-discuss-possible-leadership-bid.html|accessdate=December 12, 2015|work=Toronto Star|date=December 12, 2015}}</ref> On July 6, 2016, Kenney announced that he would be seeking the leadership of the Alberta PC Party, citing his desire to unite Alberta's two major centre-right parties.<ref name=\"Kenney finally makes his leadership pitch to 'Unite Alberta'\">{{cite web|last1=James|first1=Wood|url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/kenney-to-announce-run-for-pc-leadership-on-wednesday |title=Kenney finally makes his leadership pitch to 'Unite Alberta' |date=July 6, 2016 |website=calgaryherald.com|publisher=Calgary Herald}}</ref>\nOn July 7, 2016, Kenney announced that he would resign his seat in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] within three months once the leadership campaign period officially opened, which was severely criticized by his former employer the [[Canadian Taxpayers Federation]] for misusing taxpayer dollars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jason-kenney-canadian-taxpayers-federation-alberta-1.3668514|title=Taxpayers group miffed Kenney will collect MP perks this summer|newspaper=[[CBC News]]|access-date=November 6, 2016}}</ref> He officially resigned September 23.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/jason-kenney-to-resign-federal-seat-next-week-1.3760314|title=Kenney resigning as MP after 19 years in bid to 'unite the right' in Alberta|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=resign>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/jason-kenney-canadian-taxpayers-federation-alberta-1.3668514|title=Taxpayers group miffed Kenney will collect MP perks this summer|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Leader of the Progressive Conservative Party of Alberta==\nKenney was elected leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Alberta]] on March 18, 2017, with more than 75% of the delegate votes on the first ballot. He pledged to unite the party with the rival [[Wildrose Party]] in a provincial analogue of the federal [[Unite the Right (Canada)|Unite the Right]] movement.<ref>{{cite news|author=James Wood, Calgary Herald |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/pc-leadership-convention-candidates-make-closing-arguments-before |title=Jason Kenney wins PC leadership |newspaper=Calgary Herald |date=March 19, 2017 |accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref>  The PC and Wildrose party announced a merger deal<ref>{{cite news|last1=Graney|first1=Emma|title=Wildrose-PC members to vote on new united party on July 22|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/alberta-conservative-unity-one-step-closer|accessdate=May 18, 2017|work=[[Edmonton Journal]]|date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> which was completed on July 24, 2017.\n\n==Leader of the United Conservative Party==\nOn October 28, 2017, Kenney was elected as the first full-time leader of the new [[United Conservative Party]] of Alberta.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/united-conservative-party-announce-new-leader-1.4377206|title=Jason Kenney elected 1st leader of Alberta's United Conservative Party|newspaper=[[CBC News]]|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref> He was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] representing the riding of [[Calgary-Lougheed]] in a by-election held on December 14, 2017, after MLA [[Dave Rodney]] resigned his seat in order to create a vacancy for Kenney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jason-kenney-gets-to-work-new-leader-upc-1.4377594 |title=Calgary MLA steps down to allow Jason Kenney to run for legislature seat |publisher=CBC News |date=October 29, 2017 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/kenney-byelection-dec-14-ucp-calgary-lougheed-1.4405270 |title=Calgary-Lougheed byelection called for Dec. 14 |publisher=CBC News |date=November 16, 2017 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Normal practice in the Westminster system calls for an MP holding a safe seat to resign in order to give a newly elected leader a chance to enter the legislature.\n\n=== Controversies ===\n==== \"Kamikaze campaign\" scandal ====\nThe [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] and the Alberta Election Commissioner are investigating allegations that Jason Kenney and his team were involved in orchestrating [[Jeff Callaway]]'s campaign for the leadership of the United Conservative Party in an attempt to harm Kenney's biggest rival, [[Brian Jean]]. Documents obtained by [[The Toronto Star|The Star]] confirm that Kenney's campaign controlled major aspects of Callaway's campaign, including the providing of strategic plans, attack ads, speeches, and talking points intended to discredit Jean. These documents have since been handed over the election commissioner, according to Callaway's former campaign manager, Cameron Davies. Davies also said that Kenney had attended a meeting at Callaway's house in July 2017 where the \"kamikaze campaign\" was discussed and that Kenney had first-hand knowledge of this strategy.<ref name=\"starkamikaze\">{{cite news |last1=Leavitt |first1=Kieran |last2=McIntosh |first2=Emma |title=Jason Kenney knew about UCP \u2018kamikaze\u2019 affair before leadership race, documents given to investigators say |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2019/03/17/jason-kenney-knew-about-ucp-kamikaze-affair-before-leadership-race-documents-given-to-investigators-say.html |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Toronto Star]] |date=March 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA leaked document alleged that Jason Kenney's team first approached [[Derek Fildebrandt]] in July 2017 about running a  \"dark-horse\" campaign but ultimately decided against working with him. Fildebrandt confirmed this account but stated that it was he who rejected the idea.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keller |first1=James |title=The \u2018kamikaze candidate\u2019 continues to haunt Jason Kenney |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/alberta/article-the-kamikaze-candidate-continues-to-haunt-jason-kenney/ |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn emergency injunction was sought to halt the probe into the financing of Callaway's [[2017 United Conservative Party leadership election|UCP leadership campaign]] for the duration of the [[2019 Alberta general election]], but was denied by [[Court of Queen's Bench of Alberta|Court of Queen's Bench]] Justice Anne Kirker who ruled it was in the public interest for the investigation to continue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grant |first1=Meghan |last2=Ward |first2=Rachel |title=Calgary judge denies bid to halt UCP 'kamikaze' campaign probe during Alberta election |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/kenney-callaway-ucp-oec-investigation-court-injunction-calgary-decision-1.5083536 |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |work=[[CBC News]] |date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Fraudulent e-mails used in leadership race ====\n[[CBC News]] and [[CTV News]] have received documents indicating that fraudulent e-mail addresses attached to party memberships were used to cast ballots in the party's leadership race in 2017, which Jason Kenney won. CBC News picked a sample of e-mail addresses based on suspicious domains, and determined that 60% of those were used to cast ballots in the leadership election.<ref name=\"CBCFraud\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=Drew |last2=Dunn |first2=Carolyn |last3=Dempster |first3=Allison |last4=Labby |first4=Bryan |last5=Neveu |first5=Audrey |title=Fraudulent emails used to cast votes in UCP leadership race, CBC finds |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/ucp-leadership-voter-fraud-membership-lists-data-1.5091952 |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer UCP MLA [[Prab Gill]] sent a letter to the [[RCMP]] outlining allegations that the Kenney leadership campaign used fraudulent e-mail addresses to intercept PINs needed to vote in the leadership race, and that they were subsequently used by the Kenney campaign to vote for Kenney.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former UCP MLA: Fake emails point to Kenney voter fraud |url=https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/former-ucp-mla-fake-emails-point-to-kenney-voter-fraud-1.4374894 |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |work=[[CTV News]] |date=April 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nMany of the suspicious domains were traced to a network with ever-changing domains and it is unclear who registered these domains. The majority of the fraudulent e-mail addresses were registered in the weeks preceding the leadership vote. CBC noted that it is not clear how widespread the voting fraud is outside of their selected sample of suspicious domains - it is also possible that common e-mail providers such as [[Gmail]] or [[Hotmail]] were used with fraudulent addresses. A dozen individuals were contacted by CBC News to confirm whether or not they voted in the race - they all confirmed that they did not vote in the race and the e-mails on the voter's list were not their true e-mails.<ref name=\"CBCFraud\"/>\n\nThe Royal Canadian Mounted Police went to question at least one family to speak with them regarding the allegations of voter fraud.<ref name=\"CBCFraud\"/>\n\n== Policy positions ==\n[[File:Jason Kenney and Andrew Scheer (33927663458).jpg|thumb|Kenney with [[Andrew Scheer]] in 2019.]]\nKenney has been a social conservative in his political career, voting in favor of abortion restrictions and against same-sex marriage. \n\n=== Abortion ===\nKenney is an anti-abortion politician, voting in favour of abortion restrictions and receiving an endorsement from the socially conservative lobbyist group [[Campaign Life Coalition]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet Jason Kenney\u2019s Radical Social Conservative Allies Who Want to Send Alberta Back to the 19th Century |url=https://pressprogress.ca/meet-jason-kenneys-radical-social-conservative-allies-who-want-to-send-alberta-back-to-the-19th-century/ |accessdate=December 15, 2018 |work=PressProgress |date=November 1, 2017 |language=en}}</ref> In 2018, a bill to create \"no-protest zones\" around abortion clinics was introduced to the Alberta legislature following similar legislation in place in Ontario, Quebec, British Columbia, and Newfoundland and Labrador. As leader of the United Conservative Party, Kenney refused to debate on the bill and led his caucus to [[walkout]] of the house 14 times over the course of two months when the bill was at issue.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Dean |title=Alberta passes bill creating no-protest zones around abortion clinics |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/alberta/article-alberta-passes-bill-creating-no-protest-zones-around-abortion-clinics/ |accessdate=December 15, 2018 |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |date=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== LGBTQ issues ===\nHe voted against same-sex marriage as an MP, saying \"A majority of Canadians support the provision of benefits on grounds such as domestic partnership relationships, which are grounded on unions of economic dependency rather than relationships of a mere conjugal nature, and yet still two-thirds of Canadians, from every culture that exists in this country, from every corner of the globe who have come to this country to build a future for themselves and their families, recognize that marriage is, as the Supreme Court said the last time it spoke to this issue in the Egan case in 1995, \"by nature a heterosexual institution\".\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=1979399&Language=E&Mode=1|title=Edited Hansard * Table of Contents * Number 123 (Official Version)|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Kenney supported the removal of \"traditional definition of marriage\" from the conservative party policy book.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tonda MacCharles |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/05/28/accept-same-sex-marriage-kenney-tells-tory-convention.html |title=Tories vote to accept same-sex marriage |publisher=The Star |date=May 28, 2016 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nKenney was criticized by the provincial NDP, some LGBTQ activists, and some journalists for saying in a Postmedia interview that parents generally have a right to know if their child has joined a Gay-Straight Alliance; unless it would be contrary to the best interests of the child in the circumstances.<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Ryan |title=Kenney\u2019s gay-straight alliance comments raise fears over possible outing of LGBTQ youth |url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/kenney-s-gay-straight-alliance-comments-raise-fears-over-possible-outing-of-lgbtq-youth-1.3346505 |website=calgary.ctvnews.ca |language=en-CA |date=March 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Kenney faced pressure to expel an outspoken member of the United Conservative Party who compared the [[gay pride flag]] to the flag of [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Braid |first1=Don |title=Braid: Linking rainbow flag to swastika a dark, ugly slur |url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/politics/braid-a-dark-ugly-turn-to-rhetoric-on-lgbtq-rights |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |newspaper=[[Calgary Herald]] |date=November 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Although Kenney had previously directed the party to cancel the membership of another member, he said that the decision to expel members rested with the party's board.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Dean |title=Ousting UCP member for swastika-pride flag comment not his call: Alberta Opposition leader |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4663997/alberta-kenney-carpay-ucp-swastika-pride-flag/ |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |publisher=[[The Canadian Press]] |date=November 14, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA two-decade-old audio recording surfaced in December 2018 of Kenney boasting about overturning a gay marriage law in 1989 in [[San Francisco]]. Kenney was referring to his role in organizing a petition to repeal the city ordinance that extended recognition rights of heterosexual couples to same-sex couples. This ordinance, originating during the [[Epidemiology of HIV/AIDS#United States|1980s AIDS epidemic]], extended rights that were previously exclusive to heterosexual couples, such as hospital visitation, to same-sex couples. Kenney addressed the audio clip by stating that he regrets the comments he made and that since then, his record shows he supports domestic partner arrangements and benefits for couples regardless of sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bennett |first1=Dean |title=United Conservative Leader Kenney regrets comments on gay hospital visitation rights |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2018/12/06/united-conservative-leader-kenney-regrets-comments-on-gay-hospital-visitation-rights.html |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |publisher=[[The Canadian Press]] |date=December 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The comments led to backlash from outside and within the United Conservative Party; leading a board member and campaign manager for the party to resign his positions and membership with the party, citing the audio recording of Kenney as his reason for departure. However, Kenney has stated that he supports those issues.{{who|date=April 2019}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leavitt |first1=Kieran |title=United Conservative Party board member quits party over concerns about Jason Kenney\u2019s record on LGBTQ rights |url=https://www.thestar.com/edmonton/2018/12/13/united-conservative-party-board-member-quits-party-over-concerns-about-jason-kenneys-record-on-lgbtq-rights.html |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |work=StarMetro Edmonton |date=December 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Premiership of Jason Kenney==\n{{main|Premiership of Jason Kenney}}\n\nUnder the leadership of Kenney, the United Conservative Party won a majority government in the [[2019 Alberta general election]] which was held on On April 16, 2019. They won 63 seats and 54.88% of the popular vote. The [[premiership of Jason Kenney]] began on April 30, 2019 when was sworn in by [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]], [[Lois Mitchell]] forming the [[30th Alberta Legislature]]\u2014becoming the [[List of premiers of Alberta|18th Premier of Alberta]].\n\nDuring the 1st Session of the [[30th Alberta Legislature]] the Kenney government passed about dozens of pieces of legislation, including the Act to Repeal the Carbon Tax,<ref name=\"AB_assembly_20190620\"/><ref name=\"AL_20191024\">{{citation |url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/pro/bills/20190521_1200_01_bsr.pdf |work=[[30th Alberta Legislature]] |title=Bill Status Report for the 30th Legislature|date= October 24, 2019 | access-date = October 27, 2019 }}</ref> the Alberta Corporate Tax Amendment,<ref name=\"Bill3_20190628\">{{Cite web|title=Bill3: Job Creation Tax Cut| department = Bills and Amendments |work=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|access-date=October 24, 2019 |date=June 28, 2019| url = http://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=003&legl=30&session=1 |series=30th Legislature, 1st Session (2019)}}</ref> and the [[Public Sector Wage Arbitration Deferral Act]],<ref name=\"CP_CBC_20190620\"/> Premier Kenney established a one-year $2.5 million Public Inquiry into Anti-Alberta Energy Campaigns<ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI_FAQ\">{{Cite web| title = FAQ |series= Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns| access-date = September 12, 2019 | url = https://albertainquiry.ca/faq}}</ref><ref name=\"GOV_AB_PI\">{{Cite web| title = Public inquiry into anti-Alberta energy campaigns |series=Anti-Energy campaigns| access-date = September 12, 2019| url = https://albertainquiry.ca/}}</ref> and a Calgary-based $30 million 'war room' to \"fight misinformation related to oil and gas\".<ref name=\"CBC_Heydari_20190607\">{{Cite web| last = Heydari| first = Anis| title = Jason Kenney touts $30M 'war room' but provides few details| work = CBC News| access-date = October 27, 2019| date = June 7, 2019| url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/jason-kenney-war-room-calgary-1.5167205}}</ref> They announced their first provincial budget on October 24, 2019 which fulfilled their \"promise of slight austerity\" with \"cuts to spending programs and the elimination of hundreds of bureaucracy jobs\", according to ''The National Post''.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/> ''The Post'' said that these and the corporate tax cuts \"were the key planks of a four-year plan to bring the budget into balance.\"<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\">{{Cite news| last = Dawson| first = Tyler| title = Jason Kenney\u2019s conservatives deliver the tougher budget they warned Albertans was necessary| work = National Post|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/jason-kenneys-conservatives-deliver-the-tougher-budget-they-warned-albertans-was-necessary|access-date=October 27, 2019 | date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> The goal is to reduce government spending by $4-billion over four years.<ref name=\"NaPo_Dawson_20191024\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nKenney has never married. He was inspired to enter politics at a young age following a brief discussion with former prime minister [[John Diefenbaker]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/fought-to-unite-alberta-conservatives-jason-kenney-voted-alberta-s-new-premier-1.4383420 |title=Fought to unite Alberta conservatives: Jason Kenney voted Alberta's new premier |publisher=CTV News |date=April 17, 2019 |accessdate=April 17, 2019 |first=Dean |last=Bennett}}</ref> Kenney is considered fluently bilingual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macleans.ca/news/canada/welcome-to-my-world/|title=The inside story of Jason Kenney's campaign to win over ethnic votes - Macleans.ca|website=www.macleans.ca|access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nIn 2002, Kenney received the [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/125-43120 |title=The Queen Golden Jubilee Medal List|publisher=The Governor General of Canada}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Kenney was named one of Canada's \"100 Leaders of the Future\" by ''[[Maclean's magazine]]''; \"one of Canada's leading conservative activists\" by ''The Globe and Mail''; and \"one of 21 Canadians to watch in the 21st century\" by the ''[[Financial Post]]'' magazine.<ref>[http://www.v1.theglobeandmail.com/elections/fed2004/candidates/generated/48007_CON.html Kenney, Jason.] The Globe and Mail. Candidates. 2004.]</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2009, ''Maclean's'' magazine, in association with the [[The Historica Dominion Institute|Dominion Institute]], ''[[L'actualit\u00e9]]'' and presenting sponsor [[Enbridge]] presented Kenney with the award for \"Best Overall MP\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasonkenney.ca/EN/4961/89222bn=1|title=Calgary's Jason Kenney named Canada's best overall MP in Ottawa|date=January 6, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805171117/http://www.jasonkenney.ca/EN/4961/89222bn%3D1|archivedate=August 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Maclean's'' magazine named Kenney the \"hardest working\" MP of 2011, citing overwhelming support from all political parties who recognized Kenney's constant \"20-hour work days\" and \"permanent 5 o'clock shadow\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/politics/parliamentarians-of-the-year-hardest-working-jason-kenney/|title=Parliamentarians of the Year Awards: Hardest Working&nbsp;\u2014 Jason Kenney|work=Maclean's|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he received the [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/126-687 |title=The Queen Diamond Jubilee Medal List|publisher=The Governor General of Canada}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kenney received the [[UN Watch]] Moral Courage Award for speaking out for those who had been victimized by international tyranny.<ref name=\"&quot;UN Watch presents minister kenney with moral courage award&quot;\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/un-watch-presents-jason-kenney-with-moral-courage-award|title=UN Watch presents Minister Kenney with Moral Courage Award|last=Clarke|first=Katrina|date=May 23, 2014|website=nationalpost.com|publisher=[[National Post]]|accessdate=July 8, 2016}}</ref> At the ceremony in [[Geneva]], representatives of the [[14th Dalai Lama]] presented Kenney with a traditional Tibetan scarf.<ref name=\"&quot;UN Watch presents minister kenney with moral courage award&quot;\" /> Also in 2014, Kenney was awarded the inaugural [[Benjamin Disraeli]] Prize by [[Policy Exchange]], a centre-right UK [[think tank]], in recognition of the successful outreach to Canada's ethnic and cultural communities.<ref name=\"&quot;Minister Kenney presented with inaugural Benjamin Disraeli Award&quot;\">{{cite web|url=http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/modevents/item/the-inaugural-disraeli-prize-presented-to-hon-jason-kenney-mp|title=The Inaugural Disraeli Prize, presented to Hon Jason Kenney MP|date=June 16, 2014|website=policyexchange.org.uk|publisher=[[Policy Exchange]]|last1=Rishi|first1=Sunak|accessdate=July 4, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817012558/http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/modevents/item/the-inaugural-disraeli-prize-presented-to-hon-jason-kenney-mp|archivedate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> The award was presented by British Conservative cabinet minister [[Michael Gove]].<ref name=\"&quot;Minister Kenney presented with inaugural Benjamin Disraeli Award&quot;\" />\n\nIn August 2016, [[President of Ukraine|President]] [[Petro Poroshenko]] of [[Ukraine]] awarded Jason Kenney with  [[Order of Merit (Ukraine)|Order of Merit]], Third Class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/3402016-20387|title=\u0423\u041a\u0410\u0417 \u041f\u0420\u0415\u0417\u0418\u0414\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0410 \u0423\u041a\u0420\u0410\u0407\u041d\u0418 \u2116340/2016|publisher=Office of the President|date=August 22, 2016|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:DodgerBlue; color:white\" align=\"center\"\n|'''Ribbon'''||'''Description'''||'''Notes'''\n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|80px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] ||\n*Decoration awarded in 2002<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/125-43120|title=The Queen Golden Jubilee Medal List|publisher=The Governor General of Canada}}</ref>\n*Canadian version\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-leaf|ribbon=QEII_Diamond_Jubilee_Medal_ribbon.png|width=80}} || [[Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Medal]] ||\n*Decoration awarded in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients/126-687|title=The Diamond Jubilee Medal List|publisher=The Governor General of Canada}}</ref>\n*Canadian version\n|-\n|[[Image:Ukraine-zaslug3.png|80px]] || [[Order of Merit (Ukraine)]] || \n*Decoration awarded in August 2016\n*Third Class\n|}\n\n==Electoral record==\n{{Alberta provincial by-election 2017/Calgary-Lougheed}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2015|Calgary Midnapore|percent=yes|cha