{"title_page": "N\u00f3gr\u00e1dk\u00f6vesd", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''N\u00f3gr\u00e1dk\u00f6vesd''' is a village in [[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]], [[Hungary]] with 683 inhabitants (2014).\n\n{{Portal|Hungary}}\n{{N\u00f3gr\u00e1d}}\n\n{{coord|47|53|07|N|19|22|08|E|display=title|region:HU_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nogradkovesd}}\n[[Category:Populated places in N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]]\n\n\n{{Nograd-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=August 2015}}\n\n\n'''N\u00f3gr\u00e1dk\u00f6vesd''' is a village in [[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]], [[Hungary]] with 683 inhabitants (2014).\n\n{{Portal|Hungary}}\n{{N\u00f3gr\u00e1d}}\n\n{{coord|47|53|07|N|19|22|08|E|display=title|region:HU_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nogradkovesd}}\n[[Category:Populated places in N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]]\n{{Nograd-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N%C3%B3gr%C3%A1dk%C3%B6vesd"}
{"title_page": "Mr. Lockwood", "text_new": "'''Mr. Lockwood''' is the frame-narrator in [[Emily Bront\u00eb]]'s 1847 novel ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Worth|first=George J.|date=1958|title=Emily Bront\u00eb's Mr. Lockwood|journal=Nineteenth-Century Fiction|volume=12|issue=4|pages=315\u2013320|doi=10.2307/3044427|issn=0029-0564|jstor=3044427}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frangipane|first=Nicholas|date=2016-01-02|title=Lockwood the Liar: a Call to Reconsider Wuthering Heights as a Metafictional Work on the Limits of Narrative|journal=Bront\u00eb Studies|volume=41|issue=1|pages=29\u201338|doi=10.1080/14748932.2015.1123914|issn=1474-8932}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shannon|first=Edgar F.|date=1959|title=Lockwood's Dreams and the Exegesis of Wuthering Heights|journal=Nineteenth-Century Fiction|volume=14|issue=2|pages=95\u2013109|doi=10.2307/3044162|issn=0029-0564|jstor=3044162}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fine|first=Ronald E.|date=1969|title=Lockwood's Dreams and the Key to Wuthering Heights|journal=Nineteenth-Century Fiction|volume=24|issue=1|pages=16\u201330|doi=10.2307/2932349|issn=0029-0564|jstor=2932349}}</ref> and the recorder of the main narrative, which is related to him by [[Nelly Dean]]. Dean had worked as a servant at both Thrushcross Grange and Wuthering Heights, the two manors featured in the story. \n\nLockwood is an English gentleman who arrives on the [[Yorkshire]] [[moorland|moor]]s for a retreat from city life. The narrative is propelled by Lockwood's interest in [[Heathcliff (Wuthering Heights)|Heathcliff]], his landlord at Thrushcross Grange. They later get married.\n\n== Narrative ==\n''Wuthering Heights'' begins as Lockwood arrives at Thrushcross Grange, an estate in the [[moorland]] that he is renting from Heathcliff. Heathcliff, at the time Lockwood arrives, owns both Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange, two neighboring estates. Early in the book, Lockwood visits Wuthering Heights, where he is shocked by the behavior of Heathcliff and the other residents of the manor. \n\nLockwood nevertheless pays a second visit to Wuthering Heights, when, due to the weather, he is forced to spend the night. Without proper lodgings available, Lockwood is taken to a small room by a servant, who instructs Lockwood to not let Heathcliff know that he is there. During the night, Lockwood reads a book wherein he finds the names \"[[Catherine Earnshaw]]\" and \"Catherine Linton\" written repeatedly. In the course of the night, Lockwood sees a spectre of Catherine; he relates,\n\n{{Quote|text=The intense horror of nightmare came over me: I tried to draw back my arm, but the hand clung to it, and a most melancholy voice sobbed,\n\n\"Let me in \u2014 let me in!\"\n\n\"Who are you?\" I asked, struggling, meanwhile, to disengage myself.\n\n\"Catherine Linton,\" it replied, shiveringly (why did I think of LINTON? I had read EARNSHAW twenty times for Linton). \"I'm come home: I'd lost my way on the moor!\"\n\nAs it spoke, I discerned, obscurely, a child's face looking through the window.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bront\u00eb |first1=Emily |title=Wuthering Heights |page=20}}</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nUpon waking, Lockwood recounts the vision to Heathcliff, who orders Lockwood to leave Wuthering Heights. Before he leaves, Lockwood observes Heathcliff enter the bedroom and attempt to speak to the ghost of Catherine: \"Come in! come in!\" he sobbed.  \"Cathy, do come.  Oh, do \u2014 once more!  Oh! my heart's darling! hear me this time, Catherine, at last!\"<ref>Bront\u00eb 1998, p. 24.</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Thrushcross Grange, Lockwood inquires about the history of Heathcliff and Wuthering Heights with Nelly Dean. While Lockwood is bedridden with an illness, Nelly recounts to him the story of Heathcliff, the Earnshaws of Wuthering Heights, and the Lintons of Thrushcross Grange.  Nelly's retelling makes up the bulk of the novel. \n\nThe novel concludes as Lockwood returns to Wuthering Heights to notify Heathcliff that he wished to terminate his lease of Thrushcross Grange. Upon arriving at the Heights, Lockwood discovers that Heathcliff had died, and that Heathcliff's niece and nephew were to be married. \n\nThe final scene of ''Wuthering Heights'' shows Lockwood passing by the graves of Heathcliff, Catherine, and [[Edgar Linton]] at the local [[Churchyard|kirkyard]] and commenting on the tranquility of the scene.\n\n== References ==\n*[[Emily Bront\u00eb|Bront\u00eb, Emily]]: ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'' ([[Oxford World's Classics]], [[1998 in literature|1998]]).\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wuthering Heights}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lockwood, Mr}}\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1847]]\n[[Category:Characters in Wuthering Heights]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mr. Lockwood''' is the frame-narrator in [[Emily Bront\u00eb]]'s 1847 novel ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Worth|first=George J.|date=1958|title=Emily Bront\u00eb's Mr. Lockwood|journal=Nineteenth-Century Fiction|volume=12|issue=4|pages=315\u2013320|doi=10.2307/3044427|issn=0029-0564|jstor=3044427}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frangipane|first=Nicholas|date=2016-01-02|title=Lockwood the Liar: a Call to Reconsider Wuthering Heights as a Metafictional Work on the Limits of Narrative|journal=Bront\u00eb Studies|volume=41|issue=1|pages=29\u201338|doi=10.1080/14748932.2015.1123914|issn=1474-8932}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shannon|first=Edgar F.|date=1959|title=Lockwood's Dreams and the Exegesis of Wuthering Heights|journal=Nineteenth-Century Fiction|volume=14|issue=2|pages=95\u2013109|doi=10.2307/3044162|issn=0029-0564|jstor=3044162}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fine|first=Ronald E.|date=1969|title=Lockwood's Dreams and the Key to Wuthering Heights|journal=Nineteenth-Century Fiction|volume=24|issue=1|pages=16\u201330|doi=10.2307/2932349|issn=0029-0564|jstor=2932349}}</ref> and the recorder of the main narrative, which is related to him by [[Nelly Dean]]. Dean had worked as a servant at both Thrushcross Grange and Wuthering Heights, the two manors featured in the story. \n\nLockwood is an English gentleman who arrives on the [[Yorkshire]] [[moorland|moor]]s for a retreat from city life. The narrative is propelled by Lockwood's interest in [[Heathcliff (Wuthering Heights)|Heathcliff]], his landlord at Thrushcross Grange.\n\n== Narrative ==\n''Wuthering Heights'' begins as Lockwood arrives at Thrushcross Grange, an estate in the [[moorland]] that he is renting from Heathcliff. Heathcliff, at the time Lockwood arrives, owns both Wuthering Heights and Thrushcross Grange, two neighboring estates. Early in the book, Lockwood visits Wuthering Heights, where he is shocked by the behavior of Heathcliff and the other residents of the manor. \n\nLockwood nevertheless pays a second visit to Wuthering Heights, when, due to the weather, he is forced to spend the night. Without proper lodgings available, Lockwood is taken to a small room by a servant, who instructs Lockwood to not let Heathcliff know that he is there. During the night, Lockwood reads a book wherein he finds the names \"[[Catherine Earnshaw]]\" and \"Catherine Linton\" written repeatedly. In the course of the night, Lockwood sees a spectre of Catherine; he relates,\n\n{{Quote|text=The intense horror of nightmare came over me: I tried to draw back my arm, but the hand clung to it, and a most melancholy voice sobbed,\n\n\"Let me in \u2014 let me in!\"\n\n\"Who are you?\" I asked, struggling, meanwhile, to disengage myself.\n\n\"Catherine Linton,\" it replied, shiveringly (why did I think of LINTON? I had read EARNSHAW twenty times for Linton). \"I'm come home: I'd lost my way on the moor!\"\n\nAs it spoke, I discerned, obscurely, a child's face looking through the window.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bront\u00eb |first1=Emily |title=Wuthering Heights |page=20}}</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nUpon waking, Lockwood recounts the vision to Heathcliff, who orders Lockwood to leave Wuthering Heights. Before he leaves, Lockwood observes Heathcliff enter the bedroom and attempt to speak to the ghost of Catherine: \"Come in! come in!\" he sobbed.  \"Cathy, do come.  Oh, do \u2014 once more!  Oh! my heart's darling! hear me this time, Catherine, at last!\"<ref>Bront\u00eb 1998, p. 24.</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Thrushcross Grange, Lockwood inquires about the history of Heathcliff and Wuthering Heights with Nelly Dean. While Lockwood is bedridden with an illness, Nelly recounts to him the story of Heathcliff, the Earnshaws of Wuthering Heights, and the Lintons of Thrushcross Grange.  Nelly's retelling makes up the bulk of the novel. \n\nThe novel concludes as Lockwood returns to Wuthering Heights to notify Heathcliff that he wished to terminate his lease of Thrushcross Grange. Upon arriving at the Heights, Lockwood discovers that Heathcliff had died, and that Heathcliff's niece and nephew were to be married. \n\nThe final scene of ''Wuthering Heights'' shows Lockwood passing by the graves of Heathcliff, Catherine, and [[Edgar Linton]] at the local [[Churchyard|kirkyard]] and commenting on the tranquility of the scene.\n\n== References ==\n*[[Emily Bront\u00eb|Bront\u00eb, Emily]]: ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'' ([[Oxford World's Classics]], [[1998 in literature|1998]]).\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wuthering Heights}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lockwood, Mr}}\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1847]]\n[[Category:Characters in Wuthering Heights]]\n", "name_user": "24.17.208.220", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mr._Lockwood"}
{"title_page": "N\u00f3gr\u00e1d", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{HUN}}\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|pushpin_map            =Hungary \n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of N\u00f3gr\u00e1d\n|pushpin_mapsize        =|\n\nofficial_name=N\u00f3gr\u00e1d|\nmap=[[Image:NogradMegye.png|center|thumb|275px|Location of N\u00f3gr\u00e1d county in Hungary]]|\nsubdivision_type1=[[Counties of Hungary|County]]|\nsubdivision_name1=[[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County|N\u00f3gr\u00e1d]]|\narea_total_km2=29.52|\npopulation_total=1573|\npopulation_as_of=2004|\npopulation_density_km2=53.28|\npostal_code_type=[[Postal code]]|\npostal_code=2642|\narea_code=35\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47.90482|19.05157|region:HU|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n:''For the county, see [[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]].''\n\n'''N\u00f3gr\u00e1d''' ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434}}, Novgorod-Ugorsky;<ref>[[Vladimir Vernadsky|Vernadsky, V]]. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20150102144107/http://sinsam.kirsoft.com.ru/KSNews_725.htm Voice from the Hungarian Ruthenia]''. \"[[Russkaya Mysl]]\". 1880</ref><ref>[[Alexander Pogodin|Pogodin, A]]. ''[https://archive.org/details/ZarubezhnaiaRus Ruthenia Abroad]''. \"Soikin Publishing\". Petrograd 1915</ref> {{lang-de|Neuburg}}; {{lang-sk|Novohrad}}) is a village in [[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]], [[Hungary]]. \n[[Image:N\u00f3gr\u00e1d - Castle.jpg|300px|thumb|left|N\u00f3gr\u00e1d, castle from a bird's eye view]]\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name comes from Slavic ''Novgrad'' (\"New Castle\") from which evolved [[Slovak language|Slovak]] ''Novohrad'' (with the same meaning) and Hungarian ''N\u00f3gr\u00e1d''. 1138/1329 ''civitas Naugrad'', around 1200 ''castrum Nougrad'', 1217 ''castrum de Nevgrad''.<ref name=\"varsik\">{{cite book |first=Varsik |last=Branislav |author-link=Branislav Varsik| title= Kontinuita medzi ve\u013ekomoravsk\u00fdmi Slovienmi a stredovek\u00fdmi severouhorsk\u00fdmi Slovanmi (Slov\u00e1kmi) |chapter=Os\u00eddlenie Novohradu a Ipe\u013eskej kotliny vo svetle miestnych n\u00e1zvov |publisher=Veda |year=1994 |p=115 |ISBN=80-224-0175-7 |language=Slovak}}</ref> The village (1405 ''villa Newgrad'') and the county was named after the castle.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terkepcentrum.hu/index.asp?go=map&tid=4358 Street map] {{in lang|hu}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nograd}}\n[[Category:Populated places in N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]]\n\n\n{{Nograd-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{HUN}}\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|pushpin_map            =Hungary \n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of N\u00f3gr\u00e1d\n|pushpin_mapsize        =|\n\nofficial_name=N\u00f3gr\u00e1d|\nmap=[[Image:NogradMegye.png|center|thumb|275px|Location of N\u00f3gr\u00e1d county in Hungary]]|\nsubdivision_type1=[[Counties of Hungary|County]]|\nsubdivision_name1=[[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County|N\u00f3gr\u00e1d]]|\narea_total_km2=29.52|\npopulation_total=1573|\npopulation_as_of=2004|\npopulation_density_km2=53.28|\npostal_code_type=[[Postal code]]|\npostal_code=2642|\narea_code=35\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47.90482|19.05157|region:HU|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n:''For the county, see [[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]].''\n\n'''N\u00f3gr\u00e1d''' ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434}}, Novgorod-Ugorsky;<ref>[[Vladimir Vernadsky|Vernadsky, V]]. ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20150102144107/http://sinsam.kirsoft.com.ru/KSNews_725.htm Voice from the Hungarian Ruthenia]''. \"[[Russkaya Mysl]]\". 1880</ref><ref>[[Alexander Pogodin|Pogodin, A]]. ''[https://archive.org/details/ZarubezhnaiaRus Ruthenia Abroad]''. \"Soikin Publishing\". Petrograd 1915</ref> {{lang-de|Neuburg}}; {{lang-sk|Novohrad}}) is a village in [[N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]], [[Hungary]]. \n[[Image:N\u00f3gr\u00e1d - Castle.jpg|300px|thumb|left|N\u00f3gr\u00e1d, castle from a bird's eye view]]\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name comes from Slavic ''Novgrad'' (\"New Castle\") from which evolved [[Slovak language|Slovak]] ''Novohrad'' (with the same meaning) and Hungarian ''N\u00f3gr\u00e1d''. 1138/1329 ''civitas Naugrad'', around 1200 ''castrum Nougrad'', 1217 ''castrum de Nevgrad''.<ref name=\"varsik\">{{cite book |first=Varsik |last=Branislav |author-link=Branislav Varsik| title= Kontinuita medzi ve\u013ekomoravsk\u00fdmi Slovienmi a stredovek\u00fdmi severouhorsk\u00fdmi Slovanmi (Slov\u00e1kmi) |chapter=Os\u00eddlenie Novohradu a Ipe\u013eskej kotliny vo svetle miestnych n\u00e1zvov |publisher=Veda |year=1994 |p=115 |ISBN=80-224-0175-7 |language=Slovak}}</ref> The village (1405 ''villa Newgrad'') and the county was named after the castle.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.terkepcentrum.hu/index.asp?go=map&tid=4358 Street map] {{in lang|hu}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nograd}}\n[[Category:Populated places in N\u00f3gr\u00e1d County]]\n\n{{Nograd-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N%C3%B3gr%C3%A1d"}
